## Announcing Release 3.1.4 

This release contains improvements to help keep VTrust stable across validators and closes a potential exploit of copying metadata directly from the chain within the same block. This is a proactive fix for subnet 9 after observing this occurring on subnet 6.

### Validators: 

- Validators now allow for the metadata hash to match the hugging face repo or the hugging face repo + the hotkey that uploaded it. 
- Validators now default to evaluating on 18 pages of falcon instead of 12. 
- Validators now use weights instead of incentive for shortcutting and retrying top models. 

### Miners: 

- Using the flag –use_hotkey_in_hash will upload metadata that combines the hash of the hugging face repo with their hotkey.  
  - We recommend waiting a few days for validators to update first before using this new functionality. 
  - To avoid an attacker downloading the repo within 12 seconds to create their own hash you can also upload initially in private and make it public after the block has been committed.
So each miner has to use same hf repo for the same hot_key?
No. When a miner writes metadata to the chain, they can optionally include their hotkey in the hash to protect it against same-block copiers.
But each chain commit can use any repo you wish.
Understand. Thanks 👍

To give a bit more of an example

1) Hugging Face Repo X -> Has Hash H
2) Miner 1 can upload metadata that points to X with hash H or  with hash H + hotkey 1

Then when the validator checks for Miner 1, it will first see if the Repo hash H matches what is in metadata, or if the hash H + hotkey 1 matches.
But if Miner 2 just copied the metadata then when the validator checks it would try H + hotkey 2 which would not match.

For the miner 2 to upload valid metadata they would need to be able to download the hugging face repo X to get the 'base' hash H and then add hotkey 2 to it.

Would this be a good moment to re-evaluate the way samples are packed and evaluated in the validator? For training I can understand that concatenating (unrelated) samples with EOS tokens, and then cutting them in 4096 token parts, could make (some) sense, but in validation it is a bit strange. I say this because the models we are supposed to create are (implicitly) also scored on their ability to:
a) predict tokens of a sample starting midway
b) predict tokens coming after EOS
c) predict tokens of a sample based on the preceding sample (which is a real thing, as the rows of the dataset are fetched in batches, so sometimes they are correlated)
These things make no sense to train on (that is: no sense outside the context of this competition), but they do force trainers to train using similar sample packing, which in turn may prevent other innovations from gaining traction. For validation I think there is no downside to evaluating per sample, so that there is no "after EOS" and every evaluated sample starts with a clean model state at the start of an actual sample.
Thank you for the suggestion. This is an issue we are actively working on and will be addressing it shortly after the release of v3.2.0.

I also always had the same question - does examples with `text [eos] text`  deteriorates model performance or not? I don't have a scientific answer but I haven't noticed any performance gain/loss based on this packing. Changing evaluation towards per-sample makes sense & generally better, although I kinda doubt it would have much impact in the end.
